<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">These Easter eggs <i>really</i> give an “early desktop PC era” vibe to it all. It’s very human and connects you to the fact that you’re using something that people with faces and names made. Back when these were passion projects by a bunch of hardcore nerds.<p>But they’d rather you not really see through the product abstraction layer anymore. The Product People want to control the full image of the product and it’s just safest to de-humanize it in case that list is too big or people on that list become undesirables or whatnot.<p>I’m thinking about what this might look like today. Maybe a neat Easter egg in my iPhone that every time I activate it, it shows me a few people at random who played a role in development.  I’d love it, but I imagine this would offend the high tastes of the Product People.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44367257&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44365806%2344367257" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
