<div class="comment"><div class="commtext c00">Yeah. I think the &quot;signed case&quot; also has some distinctions compared to a typical software easter egg:<p>- the effects of it are clear<p>- there&#x27;s basically no chance of unexpected side effects (I suppose in theory it could structurally weaken the case if the signatures were carved too deeply...)<p>- if a user stumbles upon it the intention is pretty clear and obviously harmless<p>- it&#x27;s not something that might get snuck in without approval of senior management, because it&#x27;s not hidden in that sense, so there is a limiter on how many of them accumulate and how complicated they might get<p>which help to explain why you might by policy forbid software easter eggs while still being an advocate for &quot;signing your work&quot;.</div><div class="reply"><p><font size="1"><u><a href="reply?id=44367239&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D44365806%2344367239" rel="nofollow">reply</a></u></font></div></div></td></tr>
